items.title: Eucalyptus rubida
items.content_text: A magnificant specimen of a Snow Gum. The trunk is just beautiful. Found in neighbours paddock, just before the Upper Coliban Reservoir.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Red Flowering Gum. Not indigenous. A beautiful specimen at the Upper Coliban Reservoir carpark. Spectacular when in flower.

items.title: Eucalyptus pauciflora
items.content_text: A beautiful weeping Snow Gum on my brother's property, just before the Upper Coliban Reservoir.

items.title: Alisterus scapularis
items.content_text: King Parrots eating seed. Female on left and male on right.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Indigenous Snow Gums on the property.There are about ten of them. New ones have been planted to preserve them.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: The big River Red Gum, on our property. The only indigenous one  there.Others on property have been planted

items.title: Acridotheres tristis
items.content_text: Common or Indian Myna. An introduced pest that takes over native bird nests and eats their eggs and young.

items.title: Junonia villida calybe
items.content_text: Meadow Argus Butterfly.Location-Springhill Rd Kyneton, near Upper Coliban reservoir.

items.title: Amanita muscaria
items.content_text: fly Argaric Fungus. Location-Pine forest near Upper Coliban Reservoir.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: Rosy Hyancinth Orchid. Location- Mt Macedon Rd, 'Forest Glade Garden', in gully area.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Tree fern. They grow in the gullies of Mt Macedon.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Ironbark trees found in the Gisborne Cemetery.Not sure if they are indigenous or planted. They seem to be scattered randomly and have beautiful red flowers.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: A specimen of a snow gum.

items.title: Eucalyptus pauciflora
items.content_text: A small stand of Snow Gum's near the reservoir. There are not many of these around this area. A few scattered trees on the Kyneton side of the reservoir and a few stands on the Tylden side.

items.title: Opodiphthera helena
items.content_text: Emperor Gum moth, that I saw at the Cherry orchard, Dolphin's Rd, Musk, near Dalesford.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Brown Tree Frog that comes to the window every night to catch insects.

items.title: Coleoptera spp.
items.content_text: I think this is a Rhinoceros Beetle.

items.title: Platycercus elegans elegans
items.content_text: Crimson Rosella with blue on top of the head instead of being all red in clour. Unusual variation. Seen this rosella for a few months and then he vanished.

items.title: Curculionoidea spp.
items.content_text: Weevil caught in a spider's web.Location-Gisborne.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Some type of honeyeater in a hollow of a Snow Gum.

items.title: Pimelea humilis
items.content_text: Growing around rocks in the fenced off remnant vegetation area. Small groundcover about 10cm high and spreading to about 20cm.

items.title: Themeda triandra
items.content_text: Kangaroo Grass flourishing after I fenced off remnant vegetation in paddock.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Tall Bluebell.Also found in fenced off remnant vegetation area.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Bird eggs found in the grassy paddock. Species unknown?

items.title: Pelargonium rodneyanum
items.content_text: Geranium that is found in the rocky area in the paddock, fenced off area.I think it is geranium rodneyii.
